messageBody:
I'd like to unsubscribe from this group.


--- kyudosha <kyudosha@...> wrote:
> I just realized I made a mis-notation in my original
> post. I intended
> to say that 32, 33 and 34 were the letters in
> question.
>
> To distill my question, then, in light of this new
> information: which
> of the three (32,33,34) is useless to a standard
> American English
> speaker? I have noticed that 32 is generally
> preferred for the "ah"
> sound in "father" "caught" "cot", etc (as they are
> all one sound to
> many Americans). I have also noticed, however, that
> Mr. Read
> specified 33 as the "o" in "OR". This is a
> distinctly different vowel
> insofar as I have heard it pronounced in American
> English, and it lies
> as a glottal somewhere between 36 and 38. Does this
> mean that 34 is
> the only vowel symbol to be altogether unused by
> American speakers, or
> is there some usage of it that I am unaware of?
>
> Are the three generally combined as 32 for
> Americans?
>
> -Andy
>
>
